Documents AI Summary:
Background: The USDA Agricultural Research Service (ARS) is seeking to enhance its IT infrastructure at the Beltsville Agricultural Research Center (BARC) and USNA campuses, which are vital for research in genomics, food safety, environmental science, and plant and animal health.

The contract aims to support the transition of core operations during BARC's gradual vacating process while ensuring that essential research can continue without disruption. The goal is to maintain operational functionality while transitioning to a modern cloud environment aligned with USDA’s IT consolidation objectives.
Work Details: The contractor will provide comprehensive IT services across several critical layers:

1) Brocade (Ruckus) Switch Support - Tier II and III engineering support for advanced troubleshooting, configuration changes, firmware updates, and hardware replacement;

2) Virtualization - Lead migration from VMware to Microsoft Hyper-V, including assessment of workloads, migration planning, environment design, execution of migration, and ongoing management of VMware;

3) Facility & Server Consolidation - Engineering support for server room renovations to house consolidated infrastructure while advising on layout and ensuring compliance;

4) Database Administration - Ongoing support for database environments with a focus on security audits, backup strategies, and compliance with federal standards;

5) Storage - Support in consolidating storage systems into a cost-effective platform while migrating on-premises storage to the cloud. The contractor will ensure all services align with USDA-ARS policies and federal requirements.
Period of Performance: 09/30/2025 to 09/29/2026
Place of Performance: USDA ARS Beltsville, MD 20705

Background: The USDA Agricultural Research Service (ARS) is conducting a market survey to assess the availability of qualified Small Business contractors, including SBA-certified HUBZone, SBA-certified 8(a), Women-Owned, and Service-Disabled Veteran-Owned Small Businesses (SDVOSB). This initiative aims to gather information for a potential project related to the purchase of Machinery Equipment Valuation Data. 

The ARS's mission includes providing agricultural economic research, and this contract will support their efforts in understanding market dynamics and regional investment behaviors in the agricultural sector.
Work Details: The Contractor shall provide the following services: 
1. Quarterly snapshots of Iron values for all agricultural equipment from 2008 to present (16 years), including a summary guide of all Iron values; 
2. Quarterly data on financed equipment to estimate the total quantity of agricultural equipment types by state from 2008 to present; 
3. Only Iron equipment codes; 
4. Estimated capture rates of all equipment in accordance with the Salient Characteristics. 

Specific requirements include: 
- Historical data for wholesale and resale agricultural equipment values disaggregated by geographic region (2008-2024); 
- Breakdown by US regions (Southwest, Southeast, Northwest, North Central); 
- Quarterly historical data on total volume of new and used equipment financed, categorized by state and type; 
- Estimated capture rates of equipment classified by code and description.

Background: The USDA, Agricultural Research Service (ARS), Northeast Area (NEA), National Arboretum in Washington, DC is seeking a Contractor to provide high-resolution imaging of 10 fragile herbarium volumes, containing approximately 2520 bound pages (specimens) total.

The U.S. National Arboretum houses a large collection of dried, preserved plant specimens called an herbarium. The herbarium consists mostly of individually mounted specimens on sheets of paper, but a subset of the collection is in large, fragile, bound volumes with preserved plants inside. These volumes and their botanical specimens date back to the 1860s and represent unique historical artifacts not found anywhere else.

Digitizing these important objects will aid in accessibility and preservation of the information contained in the original items and will allow universal access to them. Ultimately, these specimens and their data will be hosted on the ARS Biocollections Portal, increasing their scientific and cultural value enormously.
Work Details: The service will entail high-resolution imaging of 10 fragile herbarium volumes, containing approximately 2520 bound pages (specimens) total. Each volume must be handled and imaged following strict standards:

- Imaging must be non-destructive;
- Volumes must remain bound;
- Extreme care must be taken to avoid damaging the objects;
- Imaging should commence from the first page and continue sequentially to the last page;
- Only pages with pre-attached barcodes will be imaged;
- Volumes shall remain horizontal (face-up);
- Loose plant material should remain undisturbed.

Requirements include full compliance with FADGI 3 Star or higher standards, use of device-targets for validation and calibration, image output at color 600 ppi, imaging via overhead cameras, use of a book cradle or prop to limit opening angles, wearing nitrile or latex gloves at all times when handling volumes, placing white paper behind pages with holes or gaps, cropping images to show only a single page per file while retaining a small black border around each image, naming files based on pre-attached barcodes, maintaining a stable environment for the objects during handling, providing arrangements for specialized transportation if necessary, conducting a small sign-off test/sample batch before commencing the project, and performing a minimum 10% post-process review of output files.
Place of Performance: USDA, ARS, NEA, 3501 New York Avenue NE, Washington DC, 20002.

Background: The United States Department of Agriculture (USDA), Economic Research Service (ERS), intends to award a Firm Fixed Price purchase order to FastMarkets Global Limited (FGL) on a sole source basis. 

The ERS is a federal agency that provides agricultural economic research and policy services addressing domestic and global agricultural concerns. The goal of this contract is to obtain comprehensive data services related to grains and oil, fats, and biofuels, which are essential for monitoring agricultural markets.
Work Details: The contractor will provide daily spot price assessments for soybean meal, sunseeds, barley, rape seed, and rape meal. 

Additionally, they will produce daily forward curve assessments for wheat, corn, and soybean markets. The services include access to a complete tender database with a dashboard interface for searching and downloading data. Specific requirements include: 
- 30 licenses for users; 
- access to economic data including commodities trading; 
- cash prices for major commodities across the U.S.; 
- weather data for key agricultural countries; 
- the ability to create derivative products from the accessed data.
Period of Performance: Base Year: 09/01/2024 - 08/31/2025; Option Year 1: 09/01/2025 - 08/31/2026; Option Year 2: 09/01/2026 - 08/31/2027
Place of Performance: Services will be performed at the contractor's location as well as accessible online.

Description Text:
Sources Sought Notification for a requirement to procure a support application for evidence synthesis teams to manage the work of evidence-based literature reviews including support for screening and data extraction.

This is a Sources Sought Announcement issued by the United States Department of Agriculture (USDA) for informational and planning purposes only. This is NOT a solicitation, nor is it an announcement for a forthcoming solicitation. Submission of any information in response to this notification is purely voluntary. The Government assumes no financial responsibility for any costs incurred in providing a response.

The North American Industry Classification System (NAICS) code for this project is 518210 Application hosting, excluding software publishing) with a Size Standard of $30 million.

The United States Department of Agriculture (USDA) Agriculture Research Service (ARS) Office of the Chief Information Officer (OCIO) requires support for cover all pieces of an evidence-based review workflow. The support application must be able to integrate with literature retrieval and analysis tools, support review protocols and standards from several disciplines, maximize efficiency of screening and data extraction, support large numbers of literature citations, allow for access by all team members, provide the ability to easily reassign access as projects complete their lifecycles, and allow for export of data, graphical information and reports for publication.

Submission Instructions: Interested vendors are invited to submit a response to this Sources Sought notification by 12:01p ET on 05 September 2022, to the attention of David Jordan, Contract Specialist, David.Jordan@usda.gov. All questions are asked to be submitted inwriting to the Primary Point of Contract and will be addressed accordingly.

Responses should be no more than 5 pages and include the following information:


	 Organization Name;
	 Contract Name, e-mail address and phone number;
	 Organizations UEI number;
	 Business size status for the applicable NAICS code;
	 A statement of interest in any forthcoming acquisition;
	 A statement of capability showing how all aspects of the Statement of Work be performed.


Interested vendors are instructed to provide only the data requested. No proprietary classified confidential or sensitive information should be included in your response. The Government reserves the right to use any nonproprietary technical information in any resultant solicitation(s). Any additional information will not be reviewed by the USDA.

